  "prompt": "In what ways did the alliance system cause World War 1?",
  "response": "The alliance system was a significant contributing factor to the outbreak of World War 1 in several key ways:\n\n1. Complexity of Alliances\n- Europe was divided into two main alliance blocs:\n- Triple Alliance: Germany, Austria-Hungary, Italy\n- Triple Entente: Britain, France, Russia\n\n2. Automatic Military Mobilization\n- If one country in an alliance was attacked, other alliance members were obligated to support them\n- This meant a localized conflict could quickly escalate into a broader war\n\n3. Triggering Mechanism\n- After Archduke Franz Ferdinand's assassination, Austria-Hungary declared war on Serbia\n- Russia mobilized to support Serbia\n- Germany then declared war on Russia and France\n- Britain entered to support France and Russia\n\n4. Creating Tensions\n- Alliances encouraged militarization and arms races\n- Countries felt more secure and emboldened knowing they had powerful allies\n- Mutual defense pacts created a sense of inevitable conflict\n\n5. Spreading Conflict\n- What began as a regional dispute between Austria-Hungary and Serbia quickly became a continent-wide war\n- Alliance obligations meant multiple countries were drawn into conflict automatically\n\nThe alliance system effectively turned a localized conflict into a global war by creating a domino effect of military mobilizations and declarations of war.",
